Specifically how his election impacted slavery, but none  of those things would have been issues without slavery.

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:06.260
So let’s pick up with the most controversial section
of the Compromise of 1850, the fugitive slave law.

00:01:06.260 --> 00:01:15.400
Now, longtime Crash Course viewers will remember that there was already a Fugitive Slave Law written into the United States Constitution, so what made this one so controversial?

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:21.740
Under this new law, any citizen was required to turn
in anyone he or she knew to be a slave to authorities.

00:01:21.740 --> 00:01:28.660
And that made, like, every person in New England
into a sheriff, and it also required them to enforce
a law they found abhorrent.

00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:31.460
So, they had to be sheriffs and they didn’t
even get little gold badges.

00:01:31.460 --> 00:01:34.440
Thought Bubble, can I have a gold badge?
Oh. Awesome. Thank you.

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:39.920
This law was also terrifying to people of
color in the North, because even if you’d
been, say, born free in Massachusetts,

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:47.060
the courts could send you into slavery if
even one person swore before a judge that
you were a specific slave.

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:50.540
And many people of color responded to the
fugitive slave law by moving to Canada,

00:01:50.540 --> 00:01:53.400
which at the time was still technically
an English colony,

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:59.520
thereby further problematizing the whole
idea that England was all about tyranny and
the United States was all about freedom.

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:07.540
But anyway the most important result of the fugitive slave law was that it convinced some Northerners that the government was in thehands of a sinister “slave power.”

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:14.100
Sadly, slave power was not a heavy metal
band or Britney Spears’s new single or even
a secret cabal of powerful slaves,

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:18.400
but rather a conspiracy theory about a
secret cabal of pro-slavery congressmen.

00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:22.940
That conspiracy theory is going to grow in importance,
but before we get to that let us discuss Railroads.

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:27.340
Underrated in Monopoly and underrated in
the Civil War. Let’s go to the Thought Bubble.

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:31.440
Railroads made shipping cheaper and more efficient
and allowed people to move around the country quickly,

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:39.100
and they had a huge backer (also a tiny backer)
in the form of Illinois congressman Stephen Douglas,
who wanted a transcontinental railroad because

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:43.420
1. he felt it would bind  the union together at
a time when it could use some binding,

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:47.460
and 2. he figured it would go through Illinois,
which would be good for his home state.

00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:53.860
But there was a problem: To build a railroad,
the territory through which it ran needed
to be organized, ideally as states,

00:02:53.860 --> 00:03:00.020
and if the railroad was going to run through
Illinois, then the Kansas and Nebraska territories
would need to become state-like.

00:03:00.020 --> 00:03:04.140
So Douglas pushed forward the
Kansas Nebraska Act in 1854.

00:03:04.140 --> 00:03:08.080
The Kansas-Nebraska Act formalized the
idea of popular sovereignty,

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:13.840
which basically meant that (white)
residents of states could decide for themselves
whether the state should allow slavery.

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:17.820
Douglas felt this was a nice way of avoiding saying whether he favored slavery;

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:21.660
instead, he could just be in favor of letting
other people be in favor of it.

00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:28.300
Now you’ll remember that the previously
bartered Missouri Compromise banned slavery
in new states north of this here line.

00:03:28.300 --> 00:03:36.620
And since in theory Kansas or Nebraska could have slavery if people there decided they wanted it under the Kansas-Nebraska Act despite being north of that there line,

00:03:36.620 --> 00:03:40.000
this in practice repealed the Missouri Compromise.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:46.680
As a result, there was quite a lot of violence
in Kansas, so much so that some people say
the Civil War really started there in 1857.

00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:53.440
Also, the Kansas Nebraska Act led to the
creation of a new political party: The Republicans.
Yes, those Republicans.

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:54.580
Thanks, Thought Bubble.

00:03:54.580 --> 00:04:00.340
So, Douglas’s law helped to create a new coalition
party dedicated to stopping the extension of slavery.

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:04.940
It was made of former Free-Soilers, Northern
anti-slavery Whigs and some Know-Nothings.

00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:11.800
It was also a completely sectional party,
meaning that it drew supporters almost exclusively
from the free states in the North and West,

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:18.020
which, you’ll remember from like, two minutes
ago, were tied together by common economic
interests, and the railroad.

00:04:18.020 --> 00:04:20.220
I’m telling you, don’t underestimate railroads.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:21.820
By the way, we are getting to you, Dred Scott.

00:04:21.820 --> 00:04:24.420
And now we return at last to “slave power.”

00:04:24.420 --> 00:04:28.220
For many northerners, the Kansas Nebraska
Act which repealed the Missouri Compromise,

00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:35.340
was yet more evidence that Congress was
controlled by a sinister “slave power” group doing
the bidding of rich plantation owners.

00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:38.580
Which, as conspiracy theories go,
wasn’t the most far-fetched.

00:04:38.580 --> 00:04:44.800
In fact, by 1854, the North was far more populous
than the South – it had almost double the South’s
congressional representation –

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:50.360
but in spite of this advantage, Congress had just
passed a law extending the power of slave states,

00:04:50.360 --> 00:04:56.740
and potentially – because two new states
meant four new senators – making the federal
government even more pro-slavery.

00:04:56.740 --> 00:04:59.560
And to abolitionists, that didn’t really
seem like democracy.

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:04.800
The other reason that many northerners cared
enough about Kansas and Nebraska to abandon
their old party loyalties

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:10.120
was that having them become slave states was seen
as a threat to northerner’s economic self-interest.

00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:16.360
Remember the west was seen as a place
where individuals – specifically white individuals –
could become self-sufficient farmers.

00:05:16.360 --> 00:05:21.840
As Lincoln wrote: “The whole nation is interested
that the best use be made of these territories.

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:24.580
We want them for the homes of free white people.

00:05:24.580 --> 00:05:29.320
They cannot be, to any considerable extent,
if slavery is planted within them.

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:33.640
New Free States are places for poor people
to go to and better their condition.”

00:05:33.640 --> 00:05:39.520
So, the real question was: Would these
western territories have big slave-based
plantations like happened in Mississippi?

00:05:39.520 --> 00:05:45.380
Or small family farms full of frolicking
free white people, like happened in Thomas
Jefferson’s imagination?

00:05:45.380 --> 00:05:50.400
So the new Republican party ran its first presidential
candidate in 1856 and did remarkably well.

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:57.140
John C. Fremont from California picked up 39%
of the vote, all of it from the North and West, and
lost to the Democrat James Buchanan,

00:05:57.140 --> 00:06:02.180
who had the virtue of having spent much of
the previous decade in Europe and thus not
having a position on slavery.

