good way to get started as a government.

00:07:06.100 --> 00:07:14.100
The pro-slavery Lecompton Constitution was the first that went to the U.S. Congress and it was supported by Stephen Douglas as an example of popular sovereignty at work,

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:18.560
except that the man who oversaw the
voting in Kansas called it a “vile fraud.”

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:25.740
Congress delayed Kansas’ entry into the Union
(because Congress’s primary business is delay)
until another, more fair referendum took place.

00:07:25.740 --> 00:07:32.540
And after that vote, Kansas eventually
did join the U.S. as a free state in 1861,
by which time it was frankly too late.

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:40.500
All right so while all this craziness was going on
in Kansas and Congress, the Supreme Court was
busy rendering the worst decision in its history.

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:41.920
Oh, hi there, Dred Scott.

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:47.720
Dred Scott had been a slave whose master had taken him to live in Illinois and Wisconsin, both of which barred slavery.

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:54.820
So, Scott sued, arguing that if slavery was
illegal in Illinois, then living in Illinois made
him definitionally not a slave.

00:07:54.820 --> 00:07:57.340
The case took years to find its way to
the Supreme Court

00:07:57.340 --> 00:08:02.580
and eventually, in 1857, Chief Justice
Roger B. Taney, from Maryland, handed
down his decision.

00:08:02.580 --> 00:08:08.600
The Court held that Scott was still a slave, 
but it went even further, attempting to settle
the slavery issue once and for all.

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:15.320
Taney ruled that black people “had for
more than a century before been regarded
as beings of an inferior order,

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:20.660
and altogether unfit to associate with the
white race, either in social or political relations;

00:08:20.660 --> 00:08:25.700
and so far inferior that they had no rights
which the white man was bound to respect;

00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:30.740
and that the negro might justly and lawfully
be reduced to slavery for his benefit.”

00:08:30.740 --> 00:08:40.940
So...that is an actual quote from an actual
decision by the Supreme Court of the United
States of America. Wow.

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:46.740
I mean, Taney’s ruling basically said that
all black people anywhere in the United States
could be considered property,

00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:49.920
and that the court was in the business
of protecting that property.

00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:55.720
This meant a slave owner could take
his slaves from Mississippi to Massachusetts
and they would still be slaves.

00:08:55.720 --> 00:08:59.340
Which meant that technically, there was
no such thing as a free state.

00:08:59.340 --> 00:09:02.820
At least that’s how people in the north,
especially Republicans saw it.

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:07.280
The Dred Scott decision helped convince
even more people that the entire government,

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:13.560
Congress, President Buchanan, and now
the Supreme Court, were in the hands of the
dreaded “Slave Power.”

